04099nam a22006495i 9780674065253DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222012mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740652537 a10.4159/97806740652532doi  a(DE-B1597)614004  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBM674.59b.K64 2012 7aREL0400402bisacsh04a296.4/532231 aKogman-Appel, Katrin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Mahzor from Worms :bArt and Religion in a Medieval Jewish Community /cKatrin Kogman-Appel. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Facts about the Leipzig Mahzor -- t2 Worms: Community, Society, and Scholarship -- t3 A Pesah Sermon by Eleazar ben Judah of Worms -- t4 Halakhah and Minhag: Religious Law and Custom -- t5 Musar: Pietist Ethics -- t6 Sod: Mystical Dimensions -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Leipzig Mahzor is one of the most lavish Hebrew illuminated manuscripts of all time. A prayer book used during Jewish holidays, it was produced in the Middle Ages for the Jewish community of Worms in the German Rhineland. Though Worms was a vibrant center of Judaism in the eleventh and twelfth centuries and drew celebrated rabbis, little is known about the city's Jews in the later Middle Ages. In the pages of its famous book, Katrin Kogman-Appel discovers a portal into the life of this fourteenth-century community. Medieval mahzorim were used only for special services in the synagogue and "belonged" to the whole congregation, so their visual imagery reflected the local cultural associations and beliefs. The Leipzig Mahzor pays homage to one of Worms's most illustrious scholars, Eleazar ben Judah. Its imagery reveals how his Ashkenazi Pietist worldview and involvement in mysticism shaped the community's religious practice. Kogman-Appel draws attention to the Mahzor's innovations, including its strategy for avoiding visual representation of God and its depiction of customs such as the washing of dishes before Passover, something less common in other mahzorim. In addition to decoding its iconography, Kogman-Appel approaches the manuscript as a ritual object that preserved a sense of identity and cohesion within a community facing a wide range of threats to its stability and security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1096-1800. 0aJewszGermanyzWormsxHistory. 0aJudaismxHistoryyMedieval and early modern period, 425-1789. 0aManuscripts, HebrewzGermanyzLeipzig. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Sacred Writings.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674065253zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674065253423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674065253/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK